⊕meta⊕
name = "draft-release-notes"
description = "When a GitHub release is published (or manually via --var tag=<tag>), collect the commits since the previous release and draft grouped release notes plus the exact gh command to apply them. Propose-only: nothing is written to GitHub."
trigger.github.events = ["release.published"]
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 1.5
ui = "ui/workflow"
⊕⊕

※collect※
Bash root node. Resolves the repo (webhook payload or gh repo view) and the released tag (latest published release, or $SKY_TAG on manual runs), finds the previous published tag, and prints repo/tag/prev, the current release body, and the commit list between the two tags.
※※

§collect§
bash_file = "./scripts/collect.sh"
§§

※draft※
Sonnet node. Turns the collected commit data into grouped human release notes and prints them with the ready-to-run apply command. depends_on=["collect"]; reads $SKY_OUTPUT_COLLECT. Propose-only by design.
※※

§draft§
model = "sonnet"
depends_on = ["collect"]
§§

∆draft∆
Draft GitHub release notes from the data below (repo, tag, prev, current release body, commits):

$SKY_OUTPUT_COLLECT

Rules: group bullets under Features / Fixes / Other, omitting empty groups; one bullet per change, imperative mood; keep PR/issue numbers appearing in commit subjects; drop merge/chore noise unless nothing else remains; if the current release body already contains hand-written notes, preserve them verbatim above a "## What changed" section. Do NOT edit files, run commands, or call GitHub.

Output exactly two sections:
1. The complete proposed notes in one fenced markdown block.
2. The apply instruction on two lines: save section 1 to notes.md, then run
   gh release edit <tag> --repo <repo> --notes-file notes.md
   with <tag> and <repo> filled in from the data above.
∆∆

※※
draft-release-notes — propose release notes when a release is published

DAG:
  collect ──> draft

  collect  bash: resolve repo + tag, previous published tag, current body, commit list (gh api)
  draft    claude(sonnet): grouped notes + the exact `gh release edit` apply command

Trigger:
  github release.published — fires when a release is published on a repo whose
  webhook points at this daemon. The release payload carries no extracted vars,
  so collect resolves the tag via the GitHub API (newest published release).

Manual run:
  skyway run draft-release-notes --var tag=v1.2.3
  (tag optional — without it the newest published release is used)

Notes:
  - Propose-only: the draft is printed, never written back. Apply by running the
    emitted `gh release edit` command yourself.
  - Requires an authenticated `gh` CLI on the daemon host.
  - Commit range comes from `repos/{repo}/compare/{prev}...{tag}`; first release
    (no previous tag) falls back to the last 50 commits at the tag.
※※
